North Korea says it will "definitely not disarm" unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions exacerbated their distrust of the United States and that the country would certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons without such qualities.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Body's Annual General Assembly that North Korea has taken "meaningful goodwill measures" in recent years, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, breaking down the nuclear test site, and promising not to multiply nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see any corresponding reaction from the U.S.," he said.
"Without any confidence in the U.S., there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances, we will certainly not unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri has reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to nuclear weapons removal, according to which North Korea will be rewarded if it takes gradual steps, his words have seemed significant in that it has not unconditionally rejected unilateral nuclear weapons removal as Pjongjang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim pledged to work for the "destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang should first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on the "destruction of nuclear weapons first" and exerts more pressure by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way, and even objecting to the "declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can force us on our knees is a dream of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions exacerbate our distrust."
Ri said nothing about plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader drew attention to earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings over the past five months between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in, adding: "If the party were in this issue of nuclear weapons destruction South Korea and not the US, the destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
However, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's rockets would be directed at the U.S. landmass after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "fire arrowman" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy North Korea," praised Kim abundantly for his courage for taking steps to disarm, but he said that much work still needs to be done and that sanctions still need to remain there until North Korea destroys nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't have a time frame for this, saying "it doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps they have taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that, "Applying sanctions by the Security Council must continue diligently and without ceasing until we realize the full, final, confirmed destruction of nuclear weapons."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an effort to dry up funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the outskirts of the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip there hasn't gone well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said that progress had been made, but North Korea accused him of making "bending-like demands" just hours later.
North Korea, in a meeting with Moon, promised to break down a missile site and also to take a nuclear complex if the United States "conforming measures."
He said Kim told him that the "conforming measures" he wants to see are security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore, as well as steps towards normalizing relationship with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year allows all of its undergraduate students to get more sleep in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of studying by caffeine-driven "holy afternoon sessions."
An academic found that students at the world's top university are often uninformed when it comes to the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at the Harvard Medical Faculty and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at the Harvard Medical Faculty and executive director of the university's health services, said the university had decided to enter the course after it was found that students were severely deprived of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a few interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students need to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep time routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know the health impact of choosing to smoke cigarettes," Prof Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in "studying all night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's "secret weapon" should be to avoid stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after he ran one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to strive for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and being aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
